b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe01151.htm)  [Next](sbe01153.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBW6/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 1 (SBE01)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### EIGHTEENTH KHA _N_ _D_ A.\n\n1\\. 'When one perceives, then one understands. One who does not perceive, does\nnot understand. Only he who perceives, understands. This perception, however,\nwe must desire to understand.'\n\n'Sir, I desire to understand it.'\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[121:1](sbe01150.htm#fr_319) As Narada asks no further, whether there is\nanything better, higher, truer than pra _n_ a, he is supposed to be satisfied\nwith his belief that pra _n_ a is the Highest Being. Sanatkumara, however,\nwishes to lead him on to a still higher view; hence the paragraphs which\nfollow from 16 to 26.\n\n[121:2](sbe01151.htm#fr_320) He would, for instance, call fire real, not\nknowing that fire is only a mixture of the three elements (cf. VI, 4), the\nrupatraya, a mere variety (vikara), and name (naman).\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: VII, 19](sbe01153.htm)\n\n"